Injective and surjective functions

Let f\colon X\to Yf ⁣:X→Yf\colon X\to Yf:X→Y be a function. Then ffff is

  • injective (or one-to-one) if no two elements in XXXX map to the same element under ffff. Or in other words, if x\neq yx≠yx\neq yx=y then f(x)\neq f(y)f(x)≠f(y)f(x)\neq f(y)f(x)=f(y).
  • surjective (or onto) if all elements in YYYY are hit by ffff. That is, for all y\in Yy∈Yy\in Yy∈Y there exists some x\in Xx∈Xx\in Xx∈X such that f(x)=yf(x)=yf(x)=yf(x)=y.
  • bijective if ffff is both injective and surjective.

Rememeber that every element in a set is unique. So for example, \{a,a,b,c\} = \{a,b,c\}{a,a,b,c}={a,b,c}\{a,a,b,c\} = \{a,b,c\}{a,a,b,c}={a,b,c}. Sets cannot encode duplicates! (If you want to do this, you can look up the notion of multisets. But this is probably not a part of this course.)

For a set AAAA to be a subset of another set BBBB (written A\subseteq BA⊆BA\subseteq BA⊆B, or A\subset BA⊂BA\subset BA⊂B) it is sufficient and necessary that for all elements aaaa in AAAA, aaaa is also in BBBB. Symbolically, that is A\subseteq B \iff \forall a (a\in A\implies a\in B)A⊆B  ⟺  ∀a(a∈A  ⟹  a∈B)A\subseteq B \iff \forall a (a\in A\implies a\in B)A⊆B⟺∀a(a∈A⟹a∈B).

If the set AAAA has strictly more elements than BBBB, then there is no way AAAA can be a subset of (or equal to) BBBB. This restricts the number of inclusions you have to check.

For every set AAAA, we have A\subseteq AA⊆AA\subseteq AA⊆A but this is not interesting.
